Escaping the Crowd
EC

@package
Two Shops on the Same Street
Free
# @text, @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant C (3 stories), default intro, teaching: monopoly

@text
Most people point to the business fighting hardest to survive.
They think that shop is the healthiest one on the street.
The answer feels natural, but it may look at progress the wrong way around.

@text
Two coffee shops sit on the same street, 50 paces apart.
The first sells every kind of drink the neighbourhood asks for, at a fair price.
Its door never stops opening, and the owner is proud of how busy the shop looks.
On slow mornings she watches the second shop and wonders how it survives.
The second shop opens at 10am and closes at 3pm.
It sells only one thing, beans from a small farm up the valley.

@text
Year one passes.
The first shop sells five times as much as the second.
The first owner uses her profit to buy a new espresso machine and hire a second barista.
The second shop keeps its one bean, its short hours, and its one bag design.
Customers who want that special bean travel across the city to stand in its short queue.
By the end of the year, the second shop has sold out of its small harvest.

@text
Five years later, a chain coffee shop opens on the same street.
The first shop now has to match the chain's prices and its longer hours.
Her profit drops.
Two baristas leave in one season, and the owner is slower to smile.
None of this touches the second shop.
The chain sells a different drink, from different beans, to a different customer.
10 years on, the first shop has new owners and a new menu.

@question
Why is the second shop still on the street after 10 years?

answer: It keeps its prices lower than the first shop and the chain.
consequence: The second shop charges three times more than the first. Low price is not what is protecting it.

answer: It sells something nobody else on the street can sell.
consequence: The bean from that small farm is the second shop's alone. Nobody on the street can copy it.

answer: It has a secret deal with its supplier to beat any competitor on price.
consequence: No deal is mentioned in the story. The shield is the bean, not the paperwork.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A shop that sells what no one else can sell stops fighting to survive. Most small shops never get past that fight, and that is why they fail.
hint: Look at what only one of the two shops can actually offer.

@text
The second shop is working inside a <c:g>monopoly</c:g>.
It is the first shape a builder reaches for when trying to make something nobody else already has.
Price wars on the street do not reach it, because no other shop sells the same bean.
The owner does not have to fight to survive, so she can think about next year's harvest in peace.
She can pay her one barista well, because nobody on the street can sell the same bean for less.
A shop with no competitor is the first shape a builder tries to build.

@true_false
A business that is easy to copy is usually the safest bet for a long life.

true: True, common businesses are the safe choice.
consequence: A business anyone can copy is a business anyone can open next door the week after.

false: False, a business anyone can copy is a business anyone can open next door.
consequence: The shield comes from selling what nobody else can. Without it, survival becomes a daily fight.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The easier a business is to copy, the sooner it has to fight to survive. The hardest to copy are the ones that last.
hint: Think about which shop on a busy street is easiest to open across from.

@text
The second shop survives because nobody else sells its bean.
Being alone in that bean is what most building work is about.
But is such a shop real progress, or just a clever corner? That is another question.

@package
Twelve Seconds Above the Rail
# @text, @text, @text, @text, @true_false, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant D (3 stories), misconception intro, teaching: zero to one

@text
Most people think progress is about making <c:r>more of what already works</c:r>.
A bigger field, a faster horse, or a second shop on the street.
These are real improvements, and the world runs on them.

@text
Two brothers in a bicycle shop spend five winters making wings out of cloth and wood.
Nobody in their town has seen a wooden frame rise into the air and glide.
One cold December morning, one of them stays up for 12 seconds above a wooden rail.
Twelve seconds is not much.
But the village below them has never had those 12 seconds before.

@text
A quiet chemist in a city of oil lamps spends 10 years trying to make a wire that glows.
Every kind of thread he tries burns out in minutes.
One evening he tries a strand of bamboo and it holds its light for hours.
Outside his workshop the street is still lit by fire.
Inside, for the first time, a room is lit by a wire.

@text
In a workshop full of hand-copied books, a metalworker spends a year cutting small letters from lead.
When he finally presses them against a sheet of paper, a page appears in a few minutes.
A man copying by hand would have spent a full day on the same page.
The workshop's first book is slow.
Each one after it is faster, until they come in minutes.

@true_false
Being the first to discover something matters much less than being the second and copying it faster.

true: True, copying is faster than discovering.
consequence: Copying spreads a discovery wider, but nothing can be copied until someone has made it for the first time.

false: False, nothing can be copied until it has been found for the first time.
consequence: No amount of faster copying can take the place of the first step that opens the door.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A village without risen bread cannot copy a recipe that does not yet exist. The first discovery is what makes all the copying possible.
hint: Think about what the copying is actually copying in the first place.

@text
The 12 seconds above the wooden rail are what every builder is hoping to find.
They are a move from <c:g>zero to one</c:g>.
That is the moment the world has something it did not have yesterday.
The wire that held its light made the same kind of move.
The first page pulled out of lead made the same kind of move.
Every year of bigger fields and faster horses is built on top of one of those moments.
The move from zero to one is the first step in any line of progress.

@true_false
A country that spends most of its effort making more of what already exists is still making real progress.

true: True, more of a good thing is progress.
consequence: Making more of what already works is progress of one kind. But every new step begins with someone finding the new idea first.

false: False, copying is part of progress but not where it comes from.
consequence: One to n is progress at scale. Zero to one is what the scale is copying in the first place.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Both kinds of progress are real. One finds the new idea, and the other copies it.
hint: Ask where the first recipe or the first pattern came from.

@text
The wing, the wire, and the page each turned a wall into a door the world could walk through.
Making more wings and more pages comes afterwards.
The first door is the hardest work, and it is only one of the shapes a builder needs.

@package
The Corner Nobody Walks To
# @quote, @text, @text, @text, @question, @pause, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant A (3 stories), quote intro, teaching: secrets

@quote
Chance favours the prepared mind.
Louis Pasteur

@text
Imagine walking into a library that has stood in the same square for a century.
The main hall is always busy.
Readers gather around the front desks, the new arrivals shelf, and the fiction wall.
Behind them, rows of older shelves run back into the dark.
Very few feet walk back there on any afternoon.
The librarian has never counted how many books wait in the back.

@text
Imagine walking past a field that has been farmed by the same family for four generations.
The rows run the same way every year.
The family is proud of the harvest and the neighbours come to learn the method.
Nobody has walked to the far corner of the field in two decades.
The soil there looks the same from the path, and nobody has turned it to see.
The family assumes the whole field is the same.

@text
Imagine walking into a small-town workshop where an old printing press has run for 50 years.
Three generations of printers have turned its handle and watched its plates.
Every apprentice is told the machine has been studied from every angle.
One afternoon a quiet mechanic stands and watches it for an hour.
She notices one gear is doing a job nobody has ever written down.
In 50 years of notes, that gear was missing from every diagram.

@question
How can three places in plain sight stay unnoticed for so many years?

answer: They have been deliberately hidden by someone who wanted to keep them private.
consequence: Nothing in the three scenes was hidden on purpose. They were visible the whole time.

answer: They are places nobody thinks to look, because everyone has decided there is nothing left to find.
consequence: Nobody hid them. People just stopped looking, and they have been in plain sight for years.

answer: They are parts only an expert could possibly understand.
consequence: The quiet mechanic was no expert. She only looked where others had stopped looking.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The hardest place to notice is the place everyone has already decided is empty. A second look often finds more than a first look expected.
hint: Think about whether anyone has actually looked, not whether they could have.

@pause
A field studied for a century can still hold a corner nobody has turned.

@text
The mechanic at the old press found a <c:g>secret</c:g>.
It is the kind of truth every builder is looking for.
Finding one makes something the world did not already have.
The field corner and the library back shelves hold secrets of the same shape, out in plain sight.
The secret is never in the busy aisle.
It waits in the corner everyone has already decided is empty.

@true_false
Most big discoveries come from places that had already been studied, but not looked at carefully.

true: True, studied does not always mean seen.
consequence: A place everyone thinks has been read is often the place nobody has actually turned over.

false: False, big discoveries usually come from new and unexplored places.
consequence: New places get careful eyes. Old places that look empty get no careful eyes at all.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The hardest place to find something new is a place nobody thinks holds anything new.
hint: Ask which places get a second look, and which get written off.

@reflect
A part of daily life nobody looks at closely, yet an answer might live there: an old habit.
A field the experts called finished, still holding one quiet corner: a subject learned years ago.
A room people walk through a thousand times without looking at it: an ordinary hallway.

@text
The mechanic with the old gear and the farmer at the far corner did one shared move.
They looked once more where others had stopped looking.
Most of the finds that matter sit in the corner everyone has already decided is empty.

@package
Where the Weight Hides
# @true_false, @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @text
# Variant E (3 stories), true/false intro, teaching: the power law

@true_false
In a sack of 20 seeds, the top one or two usually produce more than the other 18 put together.

true: True, a handful of seeds do most of the work in any harvest.
consequence: A careful grower watches those seeds more than the others, because the rest add very little to the total.

false: False, most harvests come from the average of many seeds working together.
consequence: Counting the average hides the real story. Most of the weight in the sack comes from the top handful.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: In many places where a total is counted, a few items at the top make up most of it.
hint: Think about what happens if the grower weighs each tree separately at harvest.

@text
A farmer counts her harvest one tree at a time, after 30 years of watching the same orchard.
Out of 200 trees, four of them produce half of the total apples.
The other 196 together produce the other half.
She weighs each tree again the next year.
The same four trees are on top, and the rest fall behind again.

@text
A beekeeper at the other end of the valley keeps 40 hives.
For 10 years he tracks the honey from each one.
Two hives give him more honey than the other 38 combined.
The two hives are not in the sunniest spot, and their queens look the same.
The difference shows up only in the weight of the honey at the end of the year.

@text
A seed merchant buys 100 small sacks from growers across three districts.
By the end of the season, three sacks have grown so tall they produce more than the other 97 combined.
The merchant spent the same money on every sack.
The difference was decided by which three sacks grew the biggest roots.
After that one season, he starts looking at the roots of every sack before anything else.

@question
In each of the three stories, where does most of the harvest actually come from?

answer: The total is spread fairly evenly across all their trees, hives, and sacks.
consequence: Every count in the three stories showed the opposite. The top few carried almost everything.

answer: A small number of trees, hives, or sacks are responsible for most of the total.
consequence: Four trees, two hives, and three sacks each carry more than all the others put together.

answer: The counting is mostly for pride, and the numbers are roughly equal in the end.
consequence: The orchard, the bee farm, and the seed store each show the same pattern.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Most of the total in any careful count hides in a small number of items. The rest barely matter.
hint: Ask whether the total is spread out or hides in a few places.

@text
A handful of trees carrying half the harvest is a <c:g>power law</c:g> at work.
A builder who wants to make something new watches for this shape more than anything else.
Every time the merchant counts carefully, a few items carry almost all the weight.
The shape shows up in orchards, in bee farms, and in every field where the count is honest.
The merchant will never look at a sack of seeds the same way again.
In the harvests that matter most, the top handful is where almost all the weight lives.

@text
Most of the weight in any harvest hides in a handful of trees.
The builder's job is to find those few and water them properly.
The last idea is about the kind of person who plants with that shape in mind from the start.

@package
The Gardener With the Drawing
# @text, @text, @text, @pause, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant B (3 stories), skip intro, teaching: definite optimism

@text
A gardener in a small town decides to plant a walled garden from scratch in the spring.
Before she orders a single seed, she spends two weeks drawing rows on paper.
She marks where each vegetable will sit, which month it will be planted, and where the sun falls at noon.
Her neighbour starts the same weekend by scattering seeds and hoping for the best.
Both of them say they are hopeful about the harvest in the autumn.

@text
By midsummer the gardener with the plan is already thinking about the next planting.
She knows exactly which rows will be empty in August and what she will put in their place.
Her neighbour walks through his garden and is surprised by what has come up where.
Some plants are lovely, and others have grown over each other.
He is still hopeful, but his garden is deciding for him.

@text
At harvest time the gardener with the plan has more than she can carry.
Every row is doing what she drew in February, and next year's plants are already in the ground.
Her neighbour has food too, but not as much, and not the kind he had in mind.
Both gardeners were hopeful in the spring.
Only one of them had a piece of paper to point at.

@pause
A plan drawn in February decides more about the autumn than the weather of August.

@text
The gardener with the drawing in February is working with <c:g>definite optimism</c:g>.
It is the shape a builder reaches for when trying to build a future the world did not already have.
Her hope is not empty.
It points at rows she can name, months she can count, and plants she has already drawn.
The neighbour's hope is real too, but it has nothing written down.
When the autumn comes, only one of the two gardens matches the hope that started it.

@true_false
Definite optimism means being certain about the future in advance.

true: True, a plan is a kind of certainty about the future.
consequence: A definite optimist is not sure about the weather. She is sure about the part "../../version_4"she is building.

false: False, nobody can be certain about the future, with or without a plan.
consequence: Certainty is not the point of a plan. The plan is what makes hope into a specific shape.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A plan is a promise to a specific shape, not a promise about the weather.
hint: Think about what a plan promises: not that it will rain, but which rows to water.

@text
A builder uses only a few shapes to make something the world did not have before.
The same few return in every field that matters.
Which of them is waiting in the work already on the table?
